With the assumption that your ```h1``` is a valid Object of ```Context```, ```h1.getSystemService(Context.VIBRATOR_SERVICE)``` does not have any compilation error.

Your device should be able to vibrate with this piece of code:  
```java
Vibrator vibrator = (Vibrator) h1.getSystemService(Context.VIBRATOR_SERVICE);
vibrator.vibrate(1000);
```
But note that the above is **deprecated**. An updated way to achieve the same purpose is as follow:
```java
VibratorManager vibratorManager = (VibratorManager) h1.getSystemService(Context.VIBRATOR_MANAGER_SERVICE);
Vibrator vibrator = vibratorManager.getDefaultVibrator();
vibrator.vibrate(VibrationEffect.createOneShot(1000, VibrationEffect.DEFAULT_AMPLITUDE));
```

And as Vibration requires permission in Android, you need to add permission ```android.permission.VIBRATE``` in your **AndroidManifest.xml**:
```xml
&lt;manifest&gt;
    &lt;uses-permission android:name=&quot;android.permission.VIBRATE&quot; /&gt;

    ...
&lt;/manifest&gt;
```

